0.body: A series on how explicit code in Rust is better at catching bugs than runtime errors in Python.
0.title: Intro

10.body: It's common to use print statements in python for debugging. For primitive data types, this works well out of the box: def main(): wrap = { "filling": "falafel" } print(d) # {'filling': 'falafel'} However, for more complex types, it can be annoying to run a long task and then get an opaque output: class Wrap(object): def __init__(self, filling): self.filling = filling def main(): wrap = Wrap("falafel") print(wrap) # <__main__.Wrap object at 0x7f7c24dcd4d0> If what we wanted each time was to see details of our Wrap , we could implement the __repr__ magic method which is called by print . class Wrap(object): def __init__(self, filling): self.filling = filling def __repr__(self): return f"<Wrap with {self.filling} filling>" def main(): wrap = Wrap("falafel") print(wrap) # <Wrap with falafel filling> This has a couple of downsides. Firstly, it can be tedious to reimplement many times. There are a couple of boilerplate libraries out there: attrs dataclasses module But more importantly, how did we even know to implement __repr__ ? It's not mentioned by help(print) , or the online documentation . A quick google for "python print class" does turn up the right answer .

11.title: rust: Derived Traits

2.body: Consider this python function: def main(): numbers = [0, 1] numbers[0] += 100 print(numbers) # [100, 1] We assign two pieces of data in an array, and modify one of them. How about this slightly more complex example? def main(): numbers = [0, 1] matrix = [numbers, numbers] matrix[0].append(2) print(matrix) You might expect the output to be: ([0, 1, 2], [0, 1]) But what we actually get is: ([0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 2]) On line 3, when we assigned an array with [numbers, numbers] , we didn't actually copy the data. We only stored two references to the same piece of data. So when we update the underlying data, all references are updated.
2.title: Simple vs complex data structures

4.body:
Cloning a vector is an expensive operation, so we need to be explicit. However, some values are cheap to copy. Rewriting our first example slightly: fn main() { let number = 3; let mut numbers = vec![number, number]; numbers[0] += 100; println!("{:?}", numbers); // [103, 3]
} Rust compiles this example fine, and changing one number does not alter the other. The difference is that: Vec implements the Clone trait - expensive to copy int64 implements the Copy trait - cheap to copy Instead of moving number into vec! twice and causing a compile error, rust assumes Copy data types are cheap enough to just copy into a function. Altering one copy does not affect the other. You can find the full list of types that implement the Copy trait in the docs . These include: bool char i64 , f64 , etc. Option<T> where T: copy , etc.
4.title: Clone vs Copy

5.body: One of rust's core features is ownership . This helps avoid accidental mutation of data, by enforcing who can use and update data at compile time.
5.title: Summary

7.body:
You may have heard the term file-like object when working in Python. This normally means an object that has read and write methods. This means that when we write: import json file_handle = open("data.json", "r")
data = json.load(file_handle) We are expected to understand that implicitly : the builtin open function returns an object with a read method the function json.load will call the read method on the object it is given if either of these constraints is violated, we will get an AttributeError at runtime import json not_a_file_handle = "spam"
data = json.load(not_a_file_handle) # AttributeError: 'str' object has no attribute 'read' This makes it hard to link external libraries together, all of which may have sligtly different interfaces. Rust has a better solution to explitly enforcing these constraints at compile time: Traits .
